    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Court-Martial For the Sub Captain?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alec Fraser letter endorses April 17 urging court-martial for Cmdr Scott D Waddle, captain of submarine that collided with Japanese trawler off Hawaii</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Incomplete Investigation'' (editorial, April 17):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Incomplete Investigation'' (editorial, April 17):</p>
        <p>As you correctly observe, accountability is the fundamental issue on which the Navy should consider a court-martial proceeding for the captain of the submarine Greeneville, which collided with a Japanese trawler, killing nine people. Accountability is the foundation of military command. It distinguishes a military leader from other professionals; it instills professionalism in commanders, on whom lives depend.</p>
        <p>Cmdr. Scott D. Waddle may not have been criminally negligent in the collision, but he should still be held publicly accountable. A court-martial would provide a public forum for the Navy to confirm to the world that accountability is still a foundation of military command.</p>
        <p>ALEC FRASER  Atlanta, April 17, 2001</p>
        <p>The writer is a retired Navy ship captain.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
